3. Build single-variate models

3.1 Model building for single categorical variable

3.1.1 Build predict function to repeat

mkPredC <- function(outCol,varCol,appCol) {
pPos <- sum(outCol==pos)/length(outCol)
naTab <- table(as.factor(outCol[is.na(varCol)]))
pPosWna <- (naTab/sum(naTab))[pos]
vTab <- table(as.factor(outCol),varCol)
pPosWv <- (vTab[pos,]+1.0e-3*pPos)/(colSums(vTab)+1.0e-3)
pred <- pPosWv[appCol]
pred[is.na(appCol)] <- pPosWna
pred[is.na(pred)] <- pPos
pred
}

3.1.2 Using predict function go through all categorical variables to get prediction for single variable

for(v in catVars) {

eTrain[,v],eTest[,v])

mkPredN <- function(outCol,varCol,appCol) {
cuts <- unique(as.numeric(
quantile(varCol, probs=seq(0, 1, 0.1),na.rm=T)))
varC <- cut(varCol,cuts)
appC <- cut(appCol,cuts)
mkPredC(outCol,varC,appC)

4.Multi-variable models

4.1.1 Feature Selection for decision tree

logLikelyhood <- function(outCol,predCol) {
sum(ifelse(outCol==pos,log(predCol),log(1-predCol)))
}

baseRateCheck <-
logLikelyhood(
eCal[,outcome],
sum(eCal[,outcome]==pos)/length(eCal[,outcome])
)
baseRateCheck
## [1] -6937.709

Here the baseRateCheck is based on the loglikelyhood of a saturated model which is a model predicted everything right, “sum(eCal[,outcome]==pos)/length(eCal[,outcome]) )” represents the saturated model. Saturation model means every target variable is predicted correctly.

Then use loglikelyhood function to run through categorical variables to pick features based on a deviance improvement.

4.2 Build Naive Baye model

pPos <- sum(eTrain[,outcome]==pos)/length(eTrain[,outcome])
nBayes <- function(pPos,pf) {
pNeg <- 1 - pPos
smoothingEpsilon <- 1.0e-5
scorePos <- log(pPos + smoothingEpsilon) +
rowSums(log(pf/pPos + smoothingEpsilon))
scoreNeg <- log(pNeg + smoothingEpsilon) +
rowSums(log((1-pf)/(1-pPos) + smoothingEpsilon))
m <- pmax(scorePos,scoreNeg)
expScorePos <- exp(scorePos-m)
expScoreNeg <- exp(scoreNeg-m)
expScorePos/(expScorePos+expScoreNeg)
}
pVars <- paste('pred',c(numericVars,catVars),sep='')
eTrain$nbpredl <- nBayes(pPos,eTrain[,pVars])
eCal$nbpredl <- nBayes(pPos,eCal[,pVars])
eTest$nbpredl <- nBayes(pPos,eTest[,pVars])
print(calcAUC(eTrain$nbpredl,eTrain[,outcome]))
## [1] 0.9055006
print(calcAUC(eCal$nbpredl,eCal[,outcome]))
## [1] 0.8785274
print(calcAUC(eTest$nbpredl,eTest[,outcome]))
## [1] 0.8832764

2.Build clustering model

2.1 calculate distance

As this dataset are all categorical variables, here is the function to calculate hamming distance and use as.dist() to transfer the calculated distance.

hamming_loop <- function(X) {
    d <- matrix(0, nrow = nrow(X), ncol = nrow(X))
    for ( i in 1:(nrow(X) - 1) ) {
        for ( j in (i + 1):nrow(X) ) {
            d[i,j] <- d[j,i] <- sum(X[i,] != X[j,])  }   } 
    d}
d<-hamming_loop(pmatrix)
d<- as.dist(d)

2.2Plotting dendrogram

pfit <- hclust(d, method="ward.D2")
plot(pfit, labels=eclusam$state,hang = 0.1, cex = 0.3)
rect.hclust(pfit, k=3)

2.3 Visualising Cluster with ggplot

library(ggplot2)
# Calculate the principle components of pmatrix
princ <- prcomp(pmatrix)
nComp <- 2
project <- as.data.frame(predict(princ, newdata=pmatrix)[,1:nComp])
project.plus <-
cbind(project,
cluster=as.factor(groups),
state=eclusam$state)
library('grDevices')
h <- do.call(
rbind,
lapply(
unique(groups),
function(c) {
f <- subset(project.plus,cluster==c);
f[chull(f),]
} ) )
p <- ggplot(project.plus, aes(x=PC1, y=PC2)) +
geom_point(aes(shape=cluster, color=cluster)) +
geom_text(aes(label=state, color=cluster),
hjust=0, vjust=1, size=3) +
geom_polygon(data=h,
aes(group=cluster,
fill=as.factor(cluster)),
alpha=0.4,linetype=0)
p

Though three clusters are covering each other at few part, most of them are well seperated.

3.Selecting K

Function to calculate squared distance

sqr_edist <- function(x, y) {
sum((x-y)^2) }
## Fucntion to calculate WSS of a cluster
wss.cluster <- function(clustermat) {
c0 <- apply(clustermat, 2, FUN=mean)
sum(apply(clustermat, 1,
FUN=function(row){sqr_edist(row,c0)}))
}

Function to count WSS

wss.total <- function(dmatrix, labels) {
wsstot <- 0
k <- length(unique(labels))
for(i in 1:k){
wsstot <- wsstot +
wss.cluster(subset(dmatrix, labels==i))
}
wsstot
}

Function to calculate total sum of squares(considered as K=1)

totss <- function(dmatrix) {
grandmean <- apply(dmatrix, 2, FUN=mean)
sum(apply(dmatrix, 1,
FUN=function(row){
sqr_edist(row, grandmean)
} ) ) }

Function to calculate CH Index

ch_criterion <- function(dmatrix, kmax, method="kmeans") {
if(!(method %in% c("kmeans", "hclust"))){
stop("method must be one of c('kmeans', 'hclust')") }
npts <- dim(dmatrix)[1] # number of rows.
totss <- totss(dmatrix)
wss <- numeric(kmax)
crit <- numeric(kmax)
wss[1] <- (npts-1)*sum(apply(dmatrix, 2, var))
for(k in 2:kmax) {
if(method=="kmeans") {
clustering<-kmeans(dmatrix, k, nstart=10, iter.max=100)
wss[k] <- clustering$tot.withinss
}else { # hclust
d<-hamming_loop(dmatrix)#hamming loop for categorical variables
d<-as.dist(d)
pfit <- hclust(d, method="ward.D2")
labels <- cutree(pfit, k=k)
wss[k] <- wss.total(dmatrix, labels)
} }
bss <- totss - wss
crit.num <- bss/(0:(kmax-1))
crit.denom <- wss/(npts - 1:kmax)
list(crit = crit.num/crit.denom, wss = wss, totss = totss)
}

Code to plot the two indicies

library(reshape2)
clustcrit <- ch_criterion(pmatrix, 10, method="hclust")
critframe <- data.frame(k=1:10, ch=scale(clustcrit$crit),
wss=scale(clustcrit$wss))
critframe <- melt(critframe, id.vars=c("k"),
variable.name="measure",
value.name="score")
p<-ggplot(critframe, aes(x=k, y=score, color=measure)) +
geom_point(aes(shape=measure)) +
geom_line(aes(linetype=measure)) +
scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:10, labels=1:10)
p

From the plot of CH and WSS indicies, WSS keeps dropping down smoothly, but has a intersection at k=5 with CH, so according to WSS we can choose k=5. However, CH measure has a elbow point at k=6 which seems to a better selection.

Then we use kmeansruns() with “ch” and “asw” criteria for picking k to see if the result varies from what we have got before.

clustering.ch <- kmeansruns(

p

The plot is just as what “bestk” column presents, k=2 is recommended for ch and k=10 is suggested for asw, they both are the highest score of each line.
